did.abstract: The International Platform Association was an organization that functioned between 1831 and 2001. The organization began as the American Lyceum Association, and served as a means for people to debate and voice their oppinions in a public setting. In the early years that followed, organizations all across the country began establishing their own lyceums; by 1834, there were several thousand. Thousands of people came to sessions to hear lectures made by eminent politicians, artists, and scientists. This collection contains office correspondence, publications of International Lyceum Association and International Platform Association, convention photographs, convention audiotape cassettes, convention videotape cassettes.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This collection contains office correspondence, publications of the International Lyceum Association and the International Platform Association, convention photographs, convention audiotape cassettes, and convention videotape cassettes. The material dates from 1904-2001. In addition to general correspondence, publications, photographs, and audiovisual material, the collection also contains files that were maintained by Dan Tyler Moore, Jr. and Jean Schaeffer.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Organized into 7 series: Governance, 1930-1990, Correspondence, 1940-1992, Publications, 1904-1978, Dan Moore's files, 1950-1960, Jean Schaeffer's files, 1978-1992, Photographs, 1962-1986, and Audiovisual, 1977-2001.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: The International Platform Association was an organization that functioned between 1831 and 2001. The organization began as the American Lyceum Association, and served as a means for people to debate and voice their oppinions in a public setting. In the early years that followed, organizations all across the country began establishing their own lyceums; by 1834, there were several thousand. The Chautauqua Movement grew out of the American Lyceum Association. This was established at Lake Chautauqua, New York, and offered adult education in both science and the humanities. Thousands of people came to sessions to hear lectures made by eminent politicians, artists, and scientists. In 1902, the International Lyceum Association was established and existed until 2001. The association organized to "dedicate itself to the improvement of the lecture, concert, and entertainment fields, to maintain the highest standard of presentations, to increase the welfare of those engaged therein, and to foster and develop goodwill and fellowship among its members." The organization changed its name to the International Platform Association in 1947.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The materials of this series include minutes, ledgers, receipts, bylaws, and a copy of the International Platform Association's amended constitution. They range in date from 1920 to 1990.

odd.head: General
odd.p: This series consists of one flatbox containing the amended constitution of the IPA, meeting minutes, ledgers, invoices, and receipts.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Arranged alphabetically by name of recipient.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The series primarily contains correspondence related to the logisitics and funding of the International Platform Association's annual meetings. The material ranges in date from 1940-1992.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Arranged alphabetically by name of publication and chronologically within each publication.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The materials of this series include multiple different publications produced by the International Platform Association as well as newspaper articles related to the organization. Publications include The Lakeside Bulletin, The Lyceum Magazine, The Lyceumite, The Lyceumite and Talent, The National Community, The Platform, The Platform World, Program, Programming, Talent, and Talent of the Platform World. Materials also include newsletters, postcards, programs, and yearbooks. The materials range in date from 1904 to 1978.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains the personal files of Dan Tyler Moore that are related to the International Platform Association. Dan Tyler Moore was the organization's executive director for several decades. The series includes correspondence, news clippings, flyers, photographs, programs, transcripts of speeches, and copies of various publications of the International Platform Association. The materials range in date from 1950 to 1960.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains the personal files of Jean Schaeffer that are related to the International Platform Association. The series includes a copy of the International Platerform Association's constitution and bylaws, correspondence, form letters, notes, programs, and copies of the publication Talent. The materials range in date from 1950 to 1992.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The materials in this series predominantly consist of photographs from International Platform Association conventions. There are also a number of unidentified photographs. Materials include both color and black and white photographs in various sizes. The materials range in date from 1962 to 1995.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Arranged in the order in which it was received.
